review.abstract:
We introduce a new model of teaching named "preference-based teaching" and a corresponding complexity parameter---the preference-based teaching dimension (PBTD)---representing the worst-case number of examples needed to teach any concept in a given concept class. Although the PBTD coincides with the well-known recursive teaching dimension (RTD) on finite classes, it is radically different on infinite ones: the RTD becomes infinite already for trivial infinite classes (such as half-intervals) whereas the PBTD evaluates to reasonably small values for a wide collection of infinite classes including classes consisting of so-called closed sets w.r.t. a given closure operator, including various classes related to linear sets over $\mathbb{N}_0$ (whose RTD had been studied quite recently) and including the class of Euclidean half-spaces. On top of presenting these concrete results, we provide the reader with a theoretical framework (of a combinatorial flavor) which helps to derive bounds on the PBTD. The concepts in which we show that the RTD does not satisfy this problem are the first to arrive at the theoretical framework (see "Proposed-based teaching theory"). Indeed, as discussed earlier, the proposed PBTD can only come into operation through a given set of closure operators (such as w.r.t. a given closure operator), i.e., the following functions satisfy the PBTD (see "Proposed-based teaching theory"). In practice, any notion of a given closure operator is bound to the general set of closure operators. We can only use these functions from within the PBTD to derive a number of classes as shown in the following diagram.

